per looks at the revealing two-decade history of efforts by the consumer privacy industry to give individuals control over their digital image through the sale of privacy protection and reputation management as a service.Through in-depth interviews with industry experts, as well as analysis of media coverage, promotional materials, and government policies, Draper examines how companies have turned the protection and promotion of digital information into a business. Along the way, she also provides insight into how these companies have responded to and shaped the ways we think about image and reputation in the digital age.Tracking the successes and failures of companies claiming to control our digital ephemera, Draper takes us inside an industry that has commodified strategies of information control. This book is a discerning overview of the debate around who controls our data, who buys and sells it, and the consequences of treating privacy as a consumer good.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConsumer protectionzUnited States. 0aData protectionzUnited States. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aInternet industryzUnited States. 0aPrivacyzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAnonymizer.  aCommodification.  aCypherpunks.  aDigital culture.  aEnvironmental movement.  aGovernment regulation.  aImage promotion.  aIndividualization.  aIndustry ethics.  aIndustry self-regulation.  aInfomediaries.  aInternet.  aManaged visibility.  aNeoliberalism.  aOnline reputation management.  aPersonal data ecosystem.  aPersonal data.  aPersonal information.  aPolitical economy.  aPublic pedagogy.  aSearch engine optimization.  aSelf-branding.  aSelf-knowledge.  aSelf-presentation.  aSelf-tracking.  aStrategic transparency.  aSurve